{"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/wwdc16-403-swift-api-design-guidelines"]}],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes","doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16"]]},"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-403-Swift-API-Design-Guidelines","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"schemaVersion":{"major":0,"patch":0,"minor":3},"abstract":[{"text":"Swift 3 introduces new API Design Guidelines specifically crafted to the unique character of Swift for clear, concise code. This talk will explore the philosophy behind the Swift API Design Guidelines and their application throughout the Swift Standard Library and the Cocoa and Cocoa Touch APIs. See how this API transformation will affect your Swift code and learn how to ensure a smooth transition to Swift 3. Learn how Swift 3 imports Objective-C APIs and how to expose rich Swift interfaces for existing Objective-C libraries.","type":"text"}],"kind":"article","sections":[],"metadata":{"role":"sampleCode","title":"Swift API Design Guidelines","roleHeading":"WWDC16","modules":[{"name":"WWDC Notes"}]},"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"text":"Swift API Design Guidelines","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Swift-API-Design-Guidelines"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"Clarity","type":"text"}]}],"type":"paragraph"},{"text":"“ed”rule","type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"edrule"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["x.reverse()           \/\/ mutating","","let y = x.reversed()  \/\/ non-mutating"]},{"text":"“ing” rule","type":"heading","level":3,"anchor":"ing-rule"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["documentDirectory.appendPathComponent(\".list\")                        \/\/ mutating","","let documentFile = documentDirectory.appendingPathComponent(\".list\")  \/\/ non-mutating"]},{"text":"The Grand Renaming","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"The-Grand-Renaming"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["extension MyController {","  @objc(handleDrag:forEvent:)","  func handleDrag(sender: UIControl, for event: UIEvent) { }  \/\/ handleDrag(sender:for:)","}"," ","\/\/ Generated Objective-C","@interface MyController ()","- (void)handleDragWithSender:(UIControl *)sender for:(UIEvent *)event;","@end","","\/\/ After adding @objc(handleDrag:forEvent:)","\/\/ Generated Objective-C","@interface MyController ()","- (void)handleDrag:(UIControl *)sender forEvent:(UIEvent *)event;","@end"]},{"text":"Mapping Objective-C APIs into Swift","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Mapping-Objective-C-APIs-into-Swift"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["\/\/ Objective-C","typedef NSString * NSCalendarIdentifier NS_EXTENSIBLE_STRING_ENUM; ","NSCalendarIdentifier NSCalendarIdentifierGregorian;","","\/\/ Generated Swift Interface","struct NSCalendarIdentifier : RawRepresentable {","    init(_ rawValue: String);","    var rawValue: String { get }","    static let gregorian: NSCalendarIdentifier","}"]},{"text":"Written By","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Written-By"},{"type":"row","columns":[{"size":1,"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"identifier":"antonio081014","type":"image"}]}]},{"size":4,"content":[{"level":3,"type":"heading","text":"Yi D.","anchor":"Yi-D"},{"inlineContent":[{"overridingTitle":"Contributed Notes","identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/antonio081014","isActive":true,"overridingTitleInlineContent":[{"text":"Contributed Notes","type":"text"}],"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"|"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/antonio081014","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"|"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"identifier":"https:\/\/medium.com\/@antonio081014","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"|"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"identifier":"https:\/\/x.com\/antonio081014","isActive":true,"type":"reference"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}],"numberOfColumns":5},{"type":"thematicBreak"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Missing anything? Corrections? "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/wwdcnotes.com\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/contributing","isActive":true}],"type":"paragraph"},{"text":"Related Sessions","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Related-Sessions"},{"style":"list","items":["doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-203-Whats-New-in-Cocoa","doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-207-Whats-New-in-Foundation-for-Swift","doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-402-Whats-New-in-Swift","doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-404-Getting-Started-with-Swift","doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-415-Going-Serverside-with-Swift-Open-Source","doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-416-Understanding-Swift-Performance","doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-720-Concurrent-Programming-With-GCD-in-Swift-3"],"type":"links"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"text":"Legal Notice","type":"text"}]}],"type":"small"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"All content copyright © 2012 – 2025 Apple Inc. All rights reserved.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"Swift, the Swift logo, Swift Playgrounds, Xcode, Instruments, Cocoa Touch, Touch ID, FaceID, iPhone, iPad, Safari, Apple Vision, Apple Watch, App Store, iPadOS, watchOS, visionOS, tvOS, Mac, and macOS are trademarks of Apple Inc., registered in the U.S. and other countries.","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"This website is not made by, affiliated with, nor endorsed by Apple.","type":"text"}],"type":"small"}],"kind":"content"}],"sampleCodeDownload":{"action":{"overridingTitle":"Watch Video (41 min)","type":"reference","identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/wwdc16\/403","isActive":true},"kind":"sampleDownload"},"references":{"doc://WWDCNotes/documentation/WWDCNotes/WWDC16-207-Whats-New-in-Foundation-for-Swift":{"kind":"article","role":"sampleCode","url":"\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/wwdc16-207-whats-new-in-foundation-for-swift","identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-207-Whats-New-in-Foundation-for-Swift","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Underlying nearly every iOS, macOS, watchOS, and tvOS application sits the Foundation framework. See how improvements to the fundamental set of API in Foundation will improve the experience of using Swift for the entire Cocoa and Cocoa Touch SDK. Learn how Foundation framework’s new value types, adoption of standard library protocols, additional type safety, better generics, and custom operators will also make your own Swift code safer, faster, and more expressive."}],"type":"topic","title":"What’s New in Foundation for Swift"},"WWDC16.jpeg":{"variants":[{"url":"\/images\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16.jpeg","traits":["1x","light"]}],"alt":null,"identifier":"WWDC16.jpeg","type":"image"},"doc://WWDCNotes/documentation/WWDCNotes/WWDC16-415-Going-Serverside-with-Swift-Open-Source":{"identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-415-Going-Serverside-with-Swift-Open-Source","title":"Going Server-side with Swift Open Source","type":"topic","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"While the Swift language makes it easy to write software that is incredibly fast and safe by design, Swift being open source means you can use it on an even broader range of platforms, from mobile devices to the desktop and in the cloud. Come for an overview of available projects at Swift.org and examples of the community in action."}],"url":"\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/wwdc16-415-going-serverside-with-swift-open-source","role":"sampleCode","kind":"article"},"doc://WWDCNotes/documentation/WWDCNotes/WWDC16-203-Whats-New-in-Cocoa":{"url":"\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/wwdc16-203-whats-new-in-cocoa","role":"sampleCode","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"macOS brings many new enhancements such as automatic window tabbing, enhanced color reproduction, and improved presentation of right-to-left languages. Get introduced to new APIs for these features and more, such as NSGridView and NSMeasurement. Learn about new conventions for APIs in Swift and Objective-C. This is your first stop to discover exciting new features in Cocoa sessions throughout the week."}],"kind":"article","title":"What’s New in Cocoa","identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-203-Whats-New-in-Cocoa","type":"topic"},"antonio081014.jpeg":{"identifier":"antonio081014.jpeg","variants":[{"traits":["1x","light"],"url":"\/images\/WWDCNotes\/antonio081014.jpeg"}],"type":"image","alt":null},"WWDC16-Icon.png":{"type":"image","variants":[{"traits":["1x","light"],"url":"\/images\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-Icon.png"}],"identifier":"WWDC16-Icon.png","alt":null},"doc://WWDCNotes/documentation/WWDCNotes/WWDC16-720-Concurrent-Programming-With-GCD-in-Swift-3":{"role":"sampleCode","url":"\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/wwdc16-720-concurrent-programming-with-gcd-in-swift-3","title":"Concurrent Programming With GCD in Swift 3","identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-720-Concurrent-Programming-With-GCD-in-Swift-3","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Swift 3 provides new interfaces that make it easier than ever to write applications with Grand Central Dispatch. Learn the basics of GCD and best practices on how to use it to architect your Swift application. You’ll also hear about new APIs and other GCD improvements."}],"kind":"article","type":"topic"},"doc://WWDCNotes/documentation/WWDCNotes/WWDC16-402-Whats-New-in-Swift":{"role":"sampleCode","url":"\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/wwdc16-402-whats-new-in-swift","title":"What’s New in Swift","identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-402-Whats-New-in-Swift","type":"topic","kind":"article","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Hear about the newest features in Swift 3, the third major release of the safe, fast, and expressive language, and the first major release built with the open source community. Gain insight into the latest changes in Xcode including enhanced migration support to help move your code to Swift 3. Learn how you can get involved in the open source community at Swift.org."}]},"doc://WWDCNotes/documentation/WWDCNotes/WWDC16-416-Understanding-Swift-Performance":{"kind":"article","role":"sampleCode","url":"\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/wwdc16-416-understanding-swift-performance","identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-416-Understanding-Swift-Performance","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"In this advanced session, find out how structs, classes, protocols, and generics are implemented in Swift. Learn about their relative costs in different dimensions of performance. See how to apply this information to speed up your code."}],"type":"topic","title":"Understanding Swift Performance"},"WWDCNotes.png":{"variants":[{"url":"\/images\/WWDCNotes\/WWDCNotes.png","traits":["1x","light"]}],"alt":null,"identifier":"WWDCNotes.png","type":"image"},"antonio081014":{"identifier":"antonio081014","variants":[{"traits":["1x","light"],"url":"\/images\/WWDCNotes\/antonio081014.jpeg"}],"type":"image","alt":"Profile image of Yi D."},"https://github.com/antonio081014":{"type":"link","title":"GitHub","identifier":"https:\/\/github.com\/antonio081014","url":"https:\/\/github.com\/antonio081014","titleInlineContent":[{"text":"GitHub","type":"text"}]},"doc://WWDCNotes/documentation/WWDCNotes/antonio081014":{"type":"topic","images":[{"identifier":"antonio081014.jpeg","type":"card"},{"identifier":"antonio081014.jpeg","type":"icon"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Reveal a brilliant idea in a very mobile engineer way."}],"title":"Yi D. (16 notes)","url":"\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/antonio081014","identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/antonio081014","kind":"article","role":"sampleCode"},"https://x.com/antonio081014":{"title":"X\/Twitter","titleInlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"X\/Twitter"}],"identifier":"https:\/\/x.com\/antonio081014","url":"https:\/\/x.com\/antonio081014","type":"link"},"doc://WWDCNotes/documentation/WWDCNotes":{"kind":"symbol","role":"collection","url":"\/documentation\/wwdcnotes","identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes","abstract":[{"text":"Session notes shared by the community for the community.","type":"text"}],"type":"topic","images":[{"type":"icon","identifier":"WWDCNotes.png"}],"title":"WWDC Notes"},"https://developer.apple.com/wwdc16/403":{"identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/wwdc16\/403","checksum":null,"type":"download","url":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/wwdc16\/403"},"doc://WWDCNotes/documentation/WWDCNotes/WWDC16-404-Getting-Started-with-Swift":{"kind":"article","role":"sampleCode","url":"\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/wwdc16-404-getting-started-with-swift","identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16-404-Getting-Started-with-Swift","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Updated to include the latest features, syntax and best practices for Swift 3, this session introduces the basics of the Swift programming language. Learn the recommended manner in which to declare variables, define functions, work with fundamental value types, protocols, generics, and more. Explore some of the great features that make Swift a safe, fast, and expressive language."}],"type":"topic","title":"Getting Started with Swift"},"https://medium.com/@antonio081014":{"type":"link","title":"Blog","identifier":"https:\/\/medium.com\/@antonio081014","url":"https:\/\/medium.com\/@antonio081014","titleInlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Blog"}]},"https://wwdcnotes.com/documentation/wwdcnotes/contributing":{"identifier":"https:\/\/wwdcnotes.com\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/contributing","titleInlineContent":[{"text":"Contributions are welcome!","type":"text"}],"type":"link","title":"Contributions are welcome!","url":"https:\/\/wwdcnotes.com\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/contributing"},"doc://WWDCNotes/documentation/WWDCNotes/WWDC16":{"role":"collectionGroup","images":[{"type":"icon","identifier":"WWDC16-Icon.png"},{"type":"card","identifier":"WWDC16.jpeg"}],"url":"\/documentation\/wwdcnotes\/wwdc16","title":"WWDC16","identifier":"doc:\/\/WWDCNotes\/documentation\/WWDCNotes\/WWDC16","abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Xcode 8, Swift 3.0, iOS 10, macOS 10.12 (Sierra), tvOS 10, watchOS 3."}],"kind":"article","type":"topic"}}}